===Time===
{{main|Babylonian calendar}} In the Archaic System time notation was written in the '''U<sub>4</sub> System U'''. Multiple [[lunisolar calendar]]s existed; however the civil calendar from the holy city of [[Nippur]] ([[Ur III period]]) was adopted by Babylon as their civil calendar.<ref>Ronan, 2008</ref> The calendar of Nippur dates to 3500 BCE and was itself based on older astronomical knowledge of an uncertain origin. The main astronomical cycles used to construct the calendar were the [[synodic month]], [[equinox year]], and [[sidereal day]].
{| class="wikitable" !colspan="7"| Basic Time |- !Unit ||Ratio ||Sumerian ||Akkadian ||Cuneiform |- | gesh ||1/360 ||mu-eš || ''geš'' ||{{cuneiform|&#x1222c;}}{{cuneiform|&#x12351;}} |- | watch ||1/12 ||da-na ||''bêru'' ||{{cuneiform|&#x12086;}} |- | day ||1 ||ud ||''immu''||{{cuneiform|&#x12313;}} |- | month ||30 ||itud ||''arhu'' ||{{cuneiform|&#x12317;}} |- | year ||360 ||mu ||''šattu'' ||{{cuneiform|&#x1222c;}} |}
==Relationship to other metrologies== The Classical Mesopotamian system formed the basis for [[Elam]]ite, Hebrew, [[Urartu|Urartian]], Hurrian, Hittite, [[Ugarit]]ic, [[Phoenicia]]n, Babylonian, Assyrian, Persian, Arabic, and Islamic metrologies.<ref>Conder 1908, p. 87.</ref> The Classical Mesopotamian System also has a proportional relationship, by virtue of standardized commerce, to [[Bronze Age]] Harappan and Egyptian metrologies.
