{{short description|Second-century Carpocratian Christian religious leader}}
{{good article}}
'''Marcellina''' was an [[early Christianity|early Christian]] [[Carpocrates|Carpocratian]] religious leader in the mid-second century AD known primarily from the writings of [[Irenaeus]] and [[Origen]]. She originated in [[Alexandria]], but moved to [[Rome]] during the episcopate of [[Pope Anicetus|Anicetus]] ({{circa}} 157 – 168). She attracted large numbers of followers and founded the Carpocratian sect of '''Marcellians'''. Like other Carpocratians, Marcellina and her followers believed in [[antinomianism]], also known as [[libertine|libertinism]], the idea that obedience to laws and regulations is unnecessary in order to attain salvation. They believed that [[Jesus]] was only a man, but saw him as a model to be emulated, albeit one which a believer was capable of surpassing. Marcellina's community appears to have sought to literally implement the foundational Carpocratian teaching of [[social egalitarianism]]. The Marcellians in particular are reported to have [[Human branding|branded]] their disciples on the insides of their right [[earlobe]]s and [[Religious images in Christian theology|venerated images]] of Jesus as well as Greek philosophers such as [[Pythagoras]], [[Plato]], and [[Aristotle]]. Although the Marcellians identified themselves as "[[Gnosis|gnostics]]", many modern scholars do not classify them as members of the sect of [[Gnosticism]].

==Historical context==
[[File:Dura Europos baptistry women at the tomb.jpg|thumb|upright=1.7|Fresco from the [[nave]] of the [[Dura-Europos church]], dating to {{circa}} 240 AD, depicting [[Mary Magdalene]] alongside two other women (the third now almost completely missing due to extensive damage) approaching the [[empty tomb]] of Jesus.{{sfn|Haskins|2005|pages=58–59}} Such women were the "explicit models" for Marcellina and other early female preachers.{{sfn|Streete|1999|page=352}}]]

Women played prominent roles in many early Christians sects as prophets, teachers, healers, missionaries, and [[presbyter]]s.{{sfn|Pagels|1989|page=60}} [[Mary Magdalene]] and [[Mary of Bethany]] were female followers of Jesus who are mentioned in the gospels and were believed to know the "[[Sacred mysteries|mysteries]]" of the [[Kingship and kingdom of God|kingdom of God]].{{sfn|Streete|1999|page=352}} Women like Mary and Martha were the explicit role models for Marcellina and her fellow female preachers.{{sfn|Streete|1999|page=352}} A creed that may have been recited at Christian initiation ceremonies is quoted by the apostle [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]] in {{bibleverse|Galatians|3:28|9}}: "There is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither bond nor free, there is neither male nor female: for ye are all one in Christ Jesus."{{sfn|Pagels|1989|page=61}} In the late first century, [[Marcion of Sinope]] ({{circa}} 85 – {{circa}} 160) appointed women as presbyters on an equal basis as men.{{sfn|Pagels|1989|page=60}}

In the second century, the [[Valentinianism|Valentinians]], a Gnostic sect, regarded women as equal to men.{{sfn|Pagels|1989|page=60}} The [[Montanism|Montanists]] regarded two prophetesses, [[Maximilla]] and [[Prisca (Prophet)|Prisca]], as the founders of their movement.{{sfn|Pagels|1989|page=60}} Female religious leaders like Marcellina were not favored by orthodox theologians, who accused them of madness, unchastity, and [[demonic possession]].{{sfn|Streete|1999|page=352}} The [[Church Fathers|Church Father]] [[Tertullian]] ({{circa}} 155 – {{circa}} 240) complained: "These heretical women—how audacious they are! They have no modesty; they are bold enough to teach, to engage in argument, to enact [[exorcism]]s, to undertake cures, and, it may be, even to baptize!"{{sfn|Pagels|1989|page=60}} He denounced one female religious leader in North Africa as "that viper".{{sfn|Pagels|1989|page=60}}

==Life and teachings==
===Carpocratian teachings===
As a Carpocratian, Marcellina taught the doctrine of [[Antinomianism|antinomianism]], or [[Libertine|libertinism]],{{sfn|Rudolph|1983|page=299}}{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} which holds that only faith and love are necessary to attain salvation and that all other perceived requirements, especially obedience to laws and regulations, are unnecessary.{{sfn|Rudolph|1983|page=299}}{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} She, like other Carpocratians, believed that the [[soul]] must follow the path to redemption, possibly going through many [[incarnation]]s.{{sfn|Rudolph|1983|page=299}}{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} The goal of the believer is the escape from the cycle of reincarnation by ascending through several stages of deification.{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} The Carpocratians believed that Jesus was only human, not divine,{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} and saw him as a exemplary model to be followed, but an example which a particularly devout believer was capable of surpassing.{{sfn|Rudolph|1983|page=299}} Jesus's prime virtue was that he could perfectly remember the Divine from his [[pre-existence]].{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} They also venerated Greek philosophers as models to be emulated as well.{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}}{{sfn|Taylor|2018|pages=214–215}} The Marcellians' syncretic cult of images was a natural consequence of this teaching.{{sfn|Rudolph|1983|page=299}}{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} One of the foundational teachings of the Carpocratians was the idea of [[social egalitarianism]], which advocated equality for all people.{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=319}}{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} Marcellina's position as the leader of the Carpocratian community in Rome indicates that, for her community at least, this was an idea which was meant to be literally implemented.{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=319}} Some Carpocratians, possibly including Marcellina, [[Communalism|held all property in common]] and [[Open relationship|shared sexual partners]].{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}} They also celebrated a form of [[agape feast]].{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}}

===''Adversus Haereses''===
[[File:Kapitolinischer Pythagoras adjusted.jpg|thumb|Irenaeus records that the Marcellians venerated images of Greek philosophers, including [[Pythagoras]], [[Plato]], and [[Aristotle]].{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}}{{sfn|McGuire|1999|page=260}}{{sfn|Williams|1996|pages=107–108, 127}} Busts of philosophers, such as this one of Pythagoras, were common objects of adoration in second-century Roman society.{{sfn|Williams|1996|pages=107–108, 127}}]]

The Church Father [[Irenaeus]] ({{circa}} 130 – {{circa}} 202) records in his apologetic treatise ''[[Adversus Haereses]]'':
<blockquote>Others of them [i.e. the Carpocratians] employ outward marks, branding their disciples inside the lobe of the right ear. From among these also arose Marcellina, who came to Rome under [the episcopate of] [[Pope Anicetus|Anicetus]], and, holding these doctrines, she led multitudes astray. They style themselves Gnostics. They also possess images, some of them painted, and others formed from different kinds of material; while they maintain that a likeness of Christ was made by [[Pontius Pilate|Pilate]] at that time when Jesus lived among them. They crown these images, and set them up along with the images of the philosophers of the world that is to say, with the images of [[Pythagoras]], and [[Plato]], and [[Aristotle]], and the rest. They have also other modes of honouring these images, after the same manner of the Gentiles.<ref>[[Irenaeus]], ''[[Adversus Haereses]]'' [http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103125.htm Book I, Chapter 25, section 6], translated by Alexander Roberts and William Rambaut</ref></blockquote>

Marcellina is the only woman associated with early Gnostic Christianity who is recorded to have been an active religious leader in her own right.{{sfn|McGuire|1999|page=261}} Other women such as Helena (allegedly a former [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] prostitute turned muse of [[Simon Magus]]), Philumena (a prophetess associated with [[Apelles (gnostic)|Apelles]]), and Flora (a student of [[Ptolemy (gnostic)|Ptolemy]]) are known to have been active as prophetesses, teachers, and disciples involved in sects led by men,{{sfn|McGuire|1999|pages=260–261}} but none of them are known to have been leaders themselves.{{sfn|McGuire|1999|page=261}} Nonetheless, Marcellina still appears in relation to Carpocrates, a male teacher, who appears to have been more actively involved than her in leading followers, writing treatises, and teaching students.{{sfn|McGuire|1999|page=261}} Anne McGuire states that it is unclear whether this description of Marcellina in relation to Carpocrates is a result of Irenaeus's own patriarchal worldview, the actual relationship between her and him, or both.{{sfn|McGuire|1999|page=261}}

Marcellina's use of images of Jesus and Greek philosophers would not have been unusual in Roman society at the time, because busts and images of philosophers were common objects of adoration in second-century Roman society.{{sfn|Williams|1996|pages=107–108, 127}}{{sfn|Taylor|2018|pages=214–215}} While Irenaeus interprets this as a sign of Marcellina's heterodox teaching,{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=108}} to any non-Christian Roman, it would have actually made her seem far less aberrant than "orthodox" Christians.{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=108}} By venerating busts of philosophers and including Jesus among them as the greatest, Marcellina's followers were honoring him in the same way that other philosophers were typically honored throughout the Greco-Roman world.{{sfn|Taylor|2018|page=215}} The Carpocratians may have had a more intellectual outlook than other sects,{{sfn|Taylor|2018|page=215}} since, according to [[Clement of Alexandria]], Carpocrates's son [[Epiphanes (gnostic)|Epiphanes]] had been trained in [[Platonism|Platonic philosophy]].<ref>[[Clement of Alexandria]], ''[[Stromata]]'' 3.5.3</ref>{{sfn|Taylor|2018|page=215}}{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=320}} Nonetheless, [[Michael Allen Williams]] states that the veneration of images seems highly unexpected for a supposedly Gnostic sect,{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=127}} since Gnostics are thought to have held the physical body in contempt.{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=127}} He suggests that Marcellina and her followers, like their pagan contemporaries, may have viewed representations of philosophers' physical likenesses as "windows to the soul" and a means of reflecting on the person's teachings.{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=127}} [[Peter Lampe]] interprets Marcillina's use of images of famous philosophers as an indication of [[religious syncretism]].{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=320}}

[[Joan E. Taylor]] notes that Irenaeus does not state that the Marcellians' portrait of Jesus was inaccurate or that portraits of Jesus were inherently immoral.{{sfn|Taylor|2018|page=215}} She also argues that the Marcellians' busts of Jesus and other philosophers may have survived long after their sect declined,{{sfn|Taylor|2018|page=215}} observing that, nearly a century later, the Roman emperor [[Alexander Severus]] (reigned 222 – 235) is said to have possessed a collection of portrait busts of various philosophers, religious figures, and historical figures including Jesus, [[Orpheus]], [[Apollonius of Tyana]], [[Alexander the Great]], and [[Abraham]].{{sfn|Taylor|2018|page=215}} She remarks, "For all we know, one of the many unidentified philosopher busts that exist in today's collections might have been thought of as Jesus in the second–third centuries."{{sfn|Taylor|2018|page=215}}

According to David Brakke, the reason why Marcellina and the members of her school identified themselves as "Gnostics" was not as a sectarian identification with the branch of early Christianity known as "[[Gnosticism]]",{{sfn|Brakke|2010|pages=48–49}} but rather as an epithet for "the ideal or true Christian, the one whose acquaintance with God has been perfected".{{sfn|Brakke|2010|page=49}} He notes that Irenaeus himself identifies Marcellina and her sect with the Carpocratians, not with the "Gnostic school of thought".{{sfn|Brakke|2010|page=49}} Also, [[Hippolytus of Rome]], who relied on Irenaeus as a source, references that the another sect known as the [[Naassenes]] "call themselves 'gnostics' in their own way, as if they alone have drunk from the amazing acquaintance of the Perfect and Good."{{sfn|Brakke|2010|pages=48–49}} In the late fourth century, the ascetic monk [[Evagrius Ponticus]] described the most advanced stage of Christian asceticism as "the Gnostic",{{sfn|Brakke|2010|page=49}} indicating that, despite the association of the word "Gnostic" with Gnosticism, it still retained its original positive meaning in the sense with which Marcellina and her disciples identified.{{sfn|Brakke|2010|page=49}} [[Bentley Layton]] does not classify Marcellina and her followers as members of the Gnostic sect either.{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=42}}

===''Contra Celsum''===
[[Origen]] ({{circa}} 184 – {{circa}} 253) also briefly mentions Marcellina in his ''[[Contra Celsum]]'', stating that "[[Celsus]] knows also of Marcellians who follow Marcellina, and [[Harpocrates|Harpocratians]] who follow [[Salome (disciple)|Salome]], and others who follow [[Mary Magdalene|Mariamme]], and others who follow [[Martha of Bethany|Martha]]."{{sfn|McGuire|1999|page=260}} Anne McGuire states that, because all the other figures listed by Origen in this passage are figures who appear in the canonical gospels, it is possible that the Marcellians may have regarded Marcellina, not only as a teacher and religious leader, but as "an authoritative source of apostolic tradition".{{sfn|McGuire|1999|page=260}} Williams notes that Origen seems to have been aware that the Marcellians called themselves Gnostics,{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=41}} since, elsewhere in ''Contra Celsum'', he notes that one of Celsus's arguments against Christianity was the existence of different sects, including ones "who call themselves gnostics".{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=41}} This would presumably include Marcellina and her followers,{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=41}} but Origen refrains from calling them by this term.{{sfn|Williams|1996|page=41}}

==Legacy==
It is unclear how Marcellina and her followers were regarded by orthodox Christians living in Rome during the 150s and 160s.{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} Irenaeus states that, among members of his own congregation in [[Gaul]] in the 180s, "we have no fellowship with them either in doctrine or in morals or in our daily social life",{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} but this statement should not be taken to apply to Christians living in Rome over twenty years prior.{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} Irenaeus also states, "[[Satan]] had set forth these people [i.e. Marcellina and her followers] to blaspheme the holy name of the church, so that the [pagan] people turn their ears from the preaching of truth when they hear their different way of teaching and think we Christians are all like them. Indeed, when they see their religiosity, they dishonor us all."{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} He adds that "They misuse the name [Christian] as a mask."{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} This indicates that Marcellina and her Carpocratian followers called themselves "Christians"{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} and, at least to outsiders, her sect appeared to be connected to other branches of Christianity.{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}}

[[Peter Lampe]] states that it is possible that members of the orthodox community in Rome simply allowed Marcillina and her sect to silently coexist,{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} but that it is also possible that they may have actively condemned them.{{sfn|Lampe|2003|page=392}} [[Robert M. Grant (theologian)|Robert M. Grant]] identifies the anti-Gnostic writings of [[Polycarp]] and [[Justin Martyr]] as partially an indirect reaction against Marcellina and her permissive moral teachings.{{sfn|Grant|1990|pages=59–61}} Marcillina and other female prophets like her were consistently portrayed negatively in the histories and canons written by proponents of orthodoxy.{{sfn|Streete|1999|page=352}} According to William H. Brackney, sources indicate that Carpocratians may have continued to exist as late as the fourth century.{{sfn|Brackney|2012|page=75}}

