[[Category:Intellectual property law]]
[[Category:Legal doctrines and principles]]

In [[topology]], a branch of mathematics, the '''quasi-relative interior''' of a subset of a [[vector space]] is a refinement of the concept of the [[Interior (topology)|interior]]. Formally, if <math>X</math> is a [[linear space]] then the quasi-relative interior of <math>A \subseteq X</math> is : <math>\operatorname{qri}(A) := \left\{x \in A: \operatorname{\overline{cone}}(A - x) \text{ is a linear subspace}\right\} </math> where <math>\operatorname{\overline{cone}}(\cdot)</math> denotes the [[Closure (topology)|closure]] of the [[conic hull]].<ref name="Zalinescu">{{cite book|last=Zălinescu|first=C.|title=Convex analysis in general vector spaces|publisher=World Scientific Publishing&nbsp; Co.,&nbsp;Inc|location=River Edge,&nbsp;NJ|year= 2002|pages=2–3|isbn=981-238-067-1|mr=1921556}}</ref>
Let <math>X</math> is a [[normed space|normed]] vector space, if <math>C \subset X</math> is a [[convex set|convex]] [[finite-dimensional]] set then <math>\operatorname{qri}(C) = \operatorname{ri}(C)</math> such that <math>\operatorname{ri}</math> is the [[relative interior]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Partially finite convex programming, Part I: Quasi relative interiors and duality theory|last1=Borwein|first1=J.M.|last2=Lewis|first2=A.S.|journal=Mathematical Programming|volume=57|year=1992|pages=15–48|url=http://legacy.orie.cornell.edu/~aslewis/publications/92-partially-I.pdf|format=pdf|accessdate=October 19, 2011|doi=10.1007/bf01581072}}</ref>
